(13, 'Iranian Airline to Resume Direct Flights to Belgium, Tehran to Brussels', 29, '<div class=\"ntDesc\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">The Iranian Qeshm Air will resume its flight from Tehran to Brussels and vice versa, airline&rsquo;s Managing Director Mahmoud Shekarabi announced.</span></div>\r\n<div class=\"ntText\">\r\n<p class=\"rtejustify\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">&ldquo;The move will be considered as a step towards the expansion of tourism relations with Europe,&rdquo; Shekarabi said in a meeting with Belgian Ambassador to Tehran Fran&ccedil;ois Delhaye.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"rtejustify\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">He reiterated that the direct flights between Iran and Belgium will be launched in the near future.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"rtejustify\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">&ldquo;The aim of launching new air route is to expand Qeshm Air&rsquo;s flights to Europe, Shekarabi said, adding, &ldquo;Belgium is a country which is located at the center of Europe and therefore, enjoys a special strategic significance.&rdquo;</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"rtejustify\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">The Belgian ambassador, for his part, said that Iran enjoys high capacities to attract foreign tourists.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"rtejustify\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">&ldquo;The Belgian people welcome establishment of the direct flights between Brussels and Tehran,&rdquo; Delhaye said.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"rtejustify\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">He underlined that Tehran-Brussels air route will have positive impact on the development of bilateral relations, specially in the areas of tourism, investment and economy.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"rtejustify\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">In late October, Tehran and Brussels signed a memorandum of understanding (MoU) to broaden their bilateral ties in economic and trade fields.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"rtejustify\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">The MoU was signed between Head of Iran&rsquo;s Trade Promotion Organization Mojtaba Khosrotaj and visiting Belgian trade delegation in Tehran.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"rtejustify\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">&ldquo;The volume of trade exchanges between Iran and Belgium nearly hit $200 million which we hope it would grow due to Belgium&rsquo;s high potentials,&rdquo; Khosrotaj said.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"rtejustify\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">He said that the MoU aims to broaden scientific, technological and infrastructural cooperation between Iranian and Belgian firms.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"rtejustify\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">The MoU has made a framework on developing investment and trade cooperation between the two countries.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"rtejustify\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\">The visiting Belgian economic-trade delegation comprises 200 representatives of 140 firms; the first economic mission of Belgium in Iran in post-JCPOA era.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"rtejustify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"rtejustify\">source:&nbsp;http://irantourismnews.com/</p>\r\n</div>', 'flights,iran,belgium,direct flights,tourism,destination', 1, 'data/news_image/13/0-1495703169-Qeshm-Air.jpg', 1, 1480110200, 1495703169, 0),
(12, '85,000 foreign tourists visited Isfahan in just one month, breaking a 40 year record', 29, '<p><span class=\"drop\">M</span>ore than 85,000 foreign tourists visited Isfahan Province in Farvardin&mdash;the first month of the Iranian year (March 21&ndash;April 20), breaking a 40-year record.</p>\r\n<p>That is more than a third of the total number of inbound tourists in Isfahan (280,000) in March 2013-17.</p>\r\n<p>This is particularly interesting because foreign tours are generally advised to avoid coming to Iran in the first two weeks of Farvardin, since it is the high travel season for Iranians out to spend the Norouz (Iranian New Year) holidays.</p>\r\n<p>Isfahan, a historical province with two world heritage sites, is a popular destination for both Iranian and foreign holidaymakers, but such an influx of overseas travelers in just one month had not happened since the 1979 Islamic Revolution.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Tourists from 44 countries visited Isfahan in Farvardin,&rdquo; Fereydoun Allahyari, the head of the provincial office of Iran&rsquo;s Cultural Heritage, Handicrafts and Tourism Organization, told ICHHTO&rsquo;s news website on Monday.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;This is unprecedented in the past four decades,&rdquo; he declared.</p>\r\n<p><strong>The French ranked first and were followed by German, Italian and Spanish tourists.</strong></p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Tourism to Isfahan has grown by 400% since the current government came to power (in August 2013),&rdquo; Allahyari said.</p>\r\n<p>The growing number of tourists has put pressure on local officials to fast-track plans to build more hotels and increase the province&rsquo;s capacity to host tourists.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The goal is to quadruple our capacity&rdquo; in the next two years, the official said, adding that &ldquo;there are plans to build 63 hotels&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p>According to Isfahan Mayor Mehdi Jamalinejad, 80% of all construction projects in the city will help tourism in one way or</p>\r\n<p>another.&nbsp; Iran&rsquo;s goal is to attract 20 million tourists annually by 2025 and infrastructure development in Isfahan, which is one of the most-visited destinations in the country, is essential to realize the ambitious goal.</p>\r\n<p>Last week, the city launched a raft of new technological upgrades to city services, including a new &ldquo;Information Kiosk&rdquo; in a prime location near the Zayandehroud river.</p>\r\n<p>Along with Tabriz, Isfahan was designated &ldquo;World Crafts City&rdquo; by the World Crafts Council in September2015, becoming the only Iranian city to have the honor.</p>\r\n<p>The historical city boasts two world heritage sites in Naqsh-e-Jahan Square and Jame&rsquo; Mosque.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>source:&nbsp;http://irantourismnews.com/</p>', 'isfahan,tourism,iran,destination', 0, 'data/news_image/12/0-1495703318-Isfahan-830X370px.jpg', 1, 1480109448, 1495871095, 0),
(14, 'Iran is fast becoming a hot destination for adventurous travelers, Iran is more progressive that you may think', 29, '<p>Laura Millar finds a much-misunderstood country that&rsquo;s a fascinating mix of ancient and modern</p>\r\n<p>CONTRARY TO WHAT THE MEDIA MIGHT INSINUATE, THE COUNTRY IS MORE PROGRESSIVE THAN YOU WOULD THINK</p>\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s Thursday night in Tehran, Iran&rsquo;s teeming capital, and inside the Azari teahouse, one of the oldest in the city, the weekend &ndash; literally &ndash; starts here. Garrulous groups of friends and families are sitting, cross-legged, on raised divans lined with colourful carpets, crowding around tables groaning with food: freshly baked flatbreads, bunches of herbs, skewers of grilled lamb and chicken, whole crispy fish, and massive platters of rice studded with tart, ruby-coloured barberries.</p>\r\n<p>In the corner, a live band are playing, one musician beating on a daf, a drum which looks like large, flat tambourine, while another plucks at a setar, a long-necked, bulbous-bodied string instrument. People at a neighbouring table see us looking blankly at the menu, written in Farsi, and offer to help me and my travel companions navigate it in their impeccable English (well, better than our Farsi, anyway).</p>\r\n<p>The atmosphere is lively, and wreathed in fragrant smoke; like most teahouses in the country, shisha pipes are part of the furniture, and provide the equivalent hit of an after-dinner liqueur. We end the night stuffing our faces with sticky, honey-covered pastries, downing delicate glasses of strong, sweet tea, and smoking ourselves silly with apple, orange blossom, and blueberry flavoured tobacco. With this kind of sugar high, who needs booze, anyway?</p>\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s my first proper night in a country which, before I arrived, I had only a hazy knowledge of. In the run up to my departure for a two-week group tour of Iran, I&rsquo;m torn between excitement and curiosity, but also a good deal of apprehension and nerves. Even if you&rsquo;re well-travelled, Iran is properly &lsquo;other&rsquo;; with a controversial, and globally worrying, nuclear programme, it&rsquo;s viewed as suspicious, closed, and secretive &ndash; or at least it has been, up until recently.</p>\r\n<p>A theocracy, it&rsquo;s currently ruled by the Supreme Leader, a powerful Muslim cleric called Ali Khamenei. He assumed the role on the death of the Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, who founded the Islamic Republic of Iran in 1979 after spearheading a bloody revolution which overthrew the ruling royal family, and what the religious minority feared were their increasingly decadent, oil-funded, pro-western ways.</p>\r\n<p>You can kind of understand why, when you see the deposed Shah, Mohammad Pahlavi&rsquo;s, White Palace in Tehran &ndash; it&rsquo;s rammed to the rafters with expensive European paintings and furniture &ndash; or the ridiculously OTT, Liberace-like, diamond and ruby-encrusted Peacock Throne which now sits in the capital&rsquo;s National Jewellery Museum.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Funny at the time, but how much of a sense of humour did Iran actually have in the aftermath of its revolution, which was followed by a traumatic, eight-year war with Iraq?</p>\r\n<p>What kind of people would I find there? Repressed and unhappy, or stoically going about their business? As it turned out, the people were perhaps the most amazing part of the whole journey.</p>\r\n<p>Over half of the country&rsquo;s population of around 80 million are under 35, and have no experience of pre-revolutionary life, unlike their parents or grandparents. They are incredibly well-educated, articulate, and many speak English.</p>\r\n<p>My guide, Mohammad, is no exception; a laid-back 33 year old, he is endlessly knowledgeable, and, over the fortnight, gives our group a comprehensive &ndash; and well-balanced &ndash; overview of Iran&rsquo;s often complex religious and political history. During a drive through Tehran, for example, he points out the old American embassy, which was shut down in 1979 and covered in anti-US graffiti, including a picture of the Statue of Liberty with a skull for a face. &ldquo;Most people do not think like that now,&rdquo; he explains &ndash; which reassures the two Americans in our party no end.</p>\r\n<p>But it doesn&rsquo;t take long to see that people here are fascinated by visitors, wherever they&rsquo;re from, and go out of their way to make you feel welcome. It&rsquo;s not often that I&rsquo;ve been moved to tears while wandering around a market (although the sight of the freshly decapitated goat heads for sale may have contributed to my emotional state), but at the buzzing bazaar in the small, elegant desert city of Yazd, our group was so mobbed by curious, delighted citizens eager to ask us for our impressions of Iran, welcome us to the country, and thank us for being there, that it felt a bit like being hailed as some kind of saint.</p>\r\n<p>In a way, we might be; through various conversations with people, I get the sense they hope that the more tourists come and visit, the greater the chance that some of the rules might eventually be relaxed. Though, contrary to what the media might insinuate, the country is more progressive than you would think.</p>\r\n<p>Women are fully entitled to education &ndash; I observe a few mixed groups of students celebrating their graduation on the steps of the tomb of the 14th-century poet Hafez, in the vibrant university city of Shiraz, and meet several who have jobs as biologists, engineers and lawyers &ndash; and they are very conscious about how they look.</p>\r\n<p>This goes beyond fashion, though I absolutely loved the way women, particularly in the larger cities, push the boundaries of hijab to the limit. Colourful silk scarves are worn right at the back of the head, designer sunglasses propped up on top, teamed with slim, cigarette-style trousers and elegant belted jackets.</p>\r\n<p>The ultimate accessory is a strip of bandage across the bridge of the nose: this signals its wearer has had rhinoplasty, the most popular cosmetic surgery in Iran, which itself has the highest rate of rhinoplasty in the world.</p>\r\n<p>As one woman sweetly explained, &ldquo;We can&rsquo;t show our beauty through our hair or clothes, so we do it through our face.&rdquo; I confess I am surprised; the women here are beautiful as they are, but it&rsquo;s a small rebellion, and a way of trying to be more western. Despite not having access to Facebook or Twitter, people do have Instagram, and while TV is largely state controlled, you can watch international films and shows.</p>\r\n<p>But while Iran&rsquo;s status as a modern, potential power-player on the international stage is hopefully underway, thanks to the lifting of economic sanctions in January 2016, and due to its vast oil reserves and relative political stability (compared to most of the Middle East), it&rsquo;s the country&rsquo;s past that most visitors will be keen to explore.</p>\r\n<p>Iran is overflowing with history. It has 19 Unesco heritage sites, many of which are centuries old and hark back to the origins of the Persian Empire, which was established by Cyrus the Great in 550BC. The most famous of these is Persepolis; around 560 miles south of Tehran, it&rsquo;s a sprawling, ancient city complex which was largely built by Cyrus&rsquo; successor, Darius I. An impressive, large-scale citadel, with a huge entrance gate, a central palace, vast terraces, elaborate columns, and more, unfortunately most of it was burned down in 330BC by Alexander the Great &ndash; as revenge for the burning of a Greek temple in Athens by Persian king, Xerxes. Whoops. Thankfully, plenty remains, which was successfully excavated in the 1930s.</p>\r\n<p class=\"pull-quote active\">IRAN HAS 19 UNESCO HERITAGE SITES, MANY OF WHICH HARK BACK TO THE PERSIAN EMPIRE</p>\r\n<p>Arriving on a hot, dusty morning, having travelled along sandy desert roads lined with pistachio trees, we&rsquo;re faced with hordes of tourists keen to use their selfie sticks. We pass through the imposing Gate of All Nations, its huge columns carved with creatures with the bodies of winged bulls and the heads of bearded men.</p>\r\n<p>Persepolis was the ceremonial capital of Persia, where Darius would receive his important visitors; Mohammad points out incredible carved bas-reliefs depicting Darius receiving gifts from foreign leaders. Although I&rsquo;m nearly left behind, thanks to a friendly group of Iranian schoolgirls who want me to describe life in London when I should be boarding the coach, I make it to the nearby site of Naqsh-e Rustam, where Darius and three of his ancestors are buried in awe-inspiring giant tombs, cut high into rock.</p>\r\n<p>Some history is more unusual; on the outskirts of Yazd, the first town we head to after Tehran, are the Game of Thrones-sounding Towers of Silence. These are two wide, flat, circular structures each built on a hill in the 17th century by the followers of the Zoroastrian religion.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>By Laura Millar</h3>\r\n<p><a href=\"https://www.gadventures.co.uk/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">gadventures.co.uk</a></p>', 'iran,tourism,destination,travel', 36, 'data/news_image/14/0-1495701358-Amir_Chakhmaq_Complex_Hadi_Karimi.jpg', 1, 1480291927, 1495701358, 0);
